00:00:26.440 --> 00:00:28.000
JANET RANKIN: A
general comment is by

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:30.430
and large, I thought you
guys did a great job.

00:00:30.430 --> 00:00:33.310
Your learning outcomes
were for the most part

00:00:33.310 --> 00:00:35.950
specific, measurable,
and realistic.

00:00:35.950 --> 00:00:39.310
The biggest problem I think
I had was with-- the biggest

00:00:39.310 --> 00:00:41.650
problem that you
had on average was

00:00:41.650 --> 00:00:43.390
the idea of the
learning outcomes

00:00:43.390 --> 00:00:45.620
really have to be measurable.

00:00:45.620 --> 00:00:48.580
So if you use a word
like appreciate,

00:00:48.580 --> 00:00:50.710
it's not measurable.

00:00:50.710 --> 00:00:53.740
So that's something to remember.

00:00:53.740 --> 00:00:57.037
If you use words like discuss,
it's potentially measurable.

00:00:57.037 --> 00:00:59.620
But you need to make sure that
you set up a venue for students

00:00:59.620 --> 00:01:01.120
to discuss.

00:01:01.120 --> 00:01:04.252
You can't just say you'll be
able to discuss that and assume

00:01:04.252 --> 00:01:05.710
that they'll be
able to discuss it,

00:01:05.710 --> 00:01:07.376
That If that's in
your learning outcome,

00:01:07.376 --> 00:01:09.850
you have to set up some
venue for them to discuss

00:01:09.850 --> 00:01:13.570
and you to know what
they're discussing.

00:01:13.570 --> 00:01:15.520
And then the two biggest
things that come up,

00:01:15.520 --> 00:01:18.490
or the two most problematic
words that come up--

00:01:18.490 --> 00:01:21.040
and I compliment you all,
because you did a great job.

00:01:21.040 --> 00:01:23.740
Nobody used understand.

00:01:23.740 --> 00:01:25.780
So that was awesome.

00:01:25.780 --> 00:01:27.550
But the other
thing, there's words

00:01:27.550 --> 00:01:31.190
like explain and describe,
which are perfectly good words

00:01:31.190 --> 00:01:33.490
to use in a learning outcome.

00:01:33.490 --> 00:01:36.370
But you have to make
sure that when you say,

00:01:36.370 --> 00:01:44.950
students will explain
the ideal gas law.

00:01:44.950 --> 00:01:47.440
They'll be able to
explain the ideal gas law.

00:01:47.440 --> 00:01:51.010
Well do you know that
they're really explaining it

00:01:51.010 --> 00:01:53.740
in the true sense of that
word that they actually

00:01:53.740 --> 00:01:56.700
internalized what it means, and
they're really explaining it?

00:01:56.700 --> 00:02:00.190
Or are they just spitting it
back, spitting back, maybe,

00:02:00.190 --> 00:02:01.990
what they read in a
book, a definition

00:02:01.990 --> 00:02:03.160
that they read in the book?

00:02:03.160 --> 00:02:04.810
So you have to make
sure that you've

00:02:04.810 --> 00:02:08.830
set up a situation wherein
they really are explaining.

00:02:08.830 --> 00:02:12.460
And they're not
just remembering.

00:02:12.460 --> 00:02:13.810
So it's a great word to use.

00:02:13.810 --> 00:02:15.310
But you have to
make sure that we're

00:02:15.310 --> 00:02:16.280
using in the right context.

00:02:16.280 --> 00:02:17.350
Same thing for describe.

00:02:17.350 --> 00:02:19.840
You can imagine that
has the same issues.

00:02:19.840 --> 00:02:21.460
Describe da, da da, da, da.

00:02:21.460 --> 00:02:23.477
Well are you sure they're
doing the describing?

00:02:23.477 --> 00:02:25.810
Or are they just remembering
somebody else's description

00:02:25.810 --> 00:02:27.520
and writing it down?

00:02:27.520 --> 00:02:30.070
One good way around
that is to tweak

00:02:30.070 --> 00:02:31.780
the parameters a little bit.

00:02:31.780 --> 00:02:36.170
To say, in a world where
there is no oxygen,

00:02:36.170 --> 00:02:41.480
what do you expect this
organism to look like,

00:02:41.480 --> 00:02:43.660
given that it has to run
really fast or something?

00:02:43.660 --> 00:02:46.360
So come up with
alternate realities

00:02:46.360 --> 00:02:49.840
that that actually force
students to transfer and then

00:02:49.840 --> 00:02:51.130
re-explain.

00:02:51.130 --> 00:02:52.090
That can be helpful.

00:02:52.090 --> 00:02:53.830
That can be really,
really helpful.

00:02:53.830 --> 00:02:56.140
I remember once in
a kinetics class,

00:02:56.140 --> 00:02:58.990
we had been deriving
the critical nucleus

00:02:58.990 --> 00:03:01.130
size for growth.

00:03:01.130 --> 00:03:03.970
And it's all based on a
radius, a critical radius.

00:03:03.970 --> 00:03:05.954
And then on the exam,
the guy said OK,

00:03:05.954 --> 00:03:07.120
they don't grow as sphere's.

00:03:07.120 --> 00:03:11.676
They grow as rectangular boxes.

00:03:11.676 --> 00:03:13.300
So then all of a
sudden, we had to look

00:03:13.300 --> 00:03:18.190
at the ratio of the length
to the height of the box

00:03:18.190 --> 00:03:18.880
or something.

00:03:18.880 --> 00:03:21.010
So that really wasn't
just we were just

00:03:21.010 --> 00:03:23.920
remembering a solution
or remembering a method.

00:03:23.920 --> 00:03:26.270
We had to actually think
about what it meant

00:03:26.270 --> 00:03:28.930
and then reapply it.

00:03:28.930 --> 00:03:30.820
So just think about how
you can get students

00:03:30.820 --> 00:03:34.810
to really describe, explain,
derive even, because you

00:03:34.810 --> 00:03:37.990
can memorize a derivation.

00:03:37.990 --> 00:03:41.929
But if you really want them to
derive it, what does that mean?

00:03:41.929 --> 00:03:43.220
How are you going to test that?

00:03:43.220 --> 00:03:45.232
So those are generally
the biggest problems

00:03:45.232 --> 00:03:46.690
people have with
learning outcomes.

00:03:46.690 --> 00:03:48.610
But by and large, you
all did a great job.

00:03:48.610 --> 00:03:50.985
If you came in late, I'll give
you your learning outcomes

