00:04:59.934 --> 00:05:02.330
isn't willing to share
your ideas, which is great.

00:05:02.330 --> 00:05:05.950
But this may be something
that's of interest to you.

00:05:05.950 --> 00:05:10.742
Before we jump into the
topic today, active learning,

00:05:10.742 --> 00:05:12.450
there were a couple
of mud card questions

00:05:12.450 --> 00:05:14.760
that I just wanted
to talk about.

00:05:14.760 --> 00:05:21.810
One was sometimes students
may nod off during class.

00:05:21.810 --> 00:05:24.390
And if it's a big
class, there's probably

00:05:24.390 --> 00:05:27.220
not a lot you can do about it.

00:05:27.220 --> 00:05:28.810
If you do enough
active learning,

00:05:28.810 --> 00:05:32.640
though, that will keep them--
that will make them wake up.

00:05:32.640 --> 00:05:36.360
Especially pair
activities or activities

00:05:36.360 --> 00:05:39.604
where they have to talk to
one or two other people,

00:05:39.604 --> 00:05:41.520
or two or three other
people, it's pretty hard

00:05:41.520 --> 00:05:43.505
to be asleep during those.

00:05:43.505 --> 00:05:44.130
And you'll see.

00:05:44.130 --> 00:05:45.810
We're going to do something
called a lightning round later

00:05:45.810 --> 00:05:46.399
on.

00:05:46.399 --> 00:05:48.690
And it's virtually impossible
to be asleep during that.

00:05:48.690 --> 00:05:50.730
So you want to make
sure that it's worth

00:05:50.730 --> 00:05:53.460
the student's time to
actually be in class

00:05:53.460 --> 00:05:54.690
and be awake for it.

00:05:54.690 --> 00:05:59.850
And active learning can
play a huge role in that.

00:05:59.850 --> 00:06:01.047
Sometimes people are tired.

00:06:01.047 --> 00:06:02.880
They stayed up too late
for whatever reason.

00:06:02.880 --> 00:06:05.590
And you can't control
everybody in your class.

00:06:05.590 --> 00:06:09.510
But you want to make sure that
you're doing everything you

00:06:09.510 --> 00:06:11.070
can do to keep them engaged.

00:06:11.070 --> 00:06:14.430
And if it's just one
student every now and then,

00:06:14.430 --> 00:06:16.494
you probably don't want
to take it personally.

00:06:16.494 --> 00:06:17.410
It's probably not you.

00:06:17.410 --> 00:06:18.990
If the whole class
is falling asleep,

00:06:18.990 --> 00:06:21.090
then it's probably
a good opportunity

00:06:21.090 --> 00:06:24.430
to rethink your strategies.

00:06:24.430 --> 00:06:26.380
Somebody asked if there
were good times of day

00:06:26.380 --> 00:06:27.700
to have a lecture.

00:06:27.700 --> 00:06:30.040
And part of it is you.

00:06:30.040 --> 00:06:31.339
Part of is your schedule.

00:06:31.339 --> 00:06:32.380
Sometimes you're allowed.

00:06:32.380 --> 00:06:33.130
You can pick that.

00:06:33.130 --> 00:06:36.280
And sometimes you really don't
have much control over when

00:06:36.280 --> 00:06:37.720
you choose to teach your class.

00:06:37.720 --> 00:06:39.940
People do say that
students, undergrads,

00:06:39.940 --> 00:06:43.900
people between the
ages of 18 and 21

00:06:43.900 --> 00:06:46.540
are not particularly interested
in being up at 8:00 or 9:00

00:06:46.540 --> 00:06:48.130
in the morning.

00:06:48.130 --> 00:06:51.370
But again you may not have
any control over that.

00:06:51.370 --> 00:06:55.425
Generally speaking, that's a
pretty low time for people.

00:06:58.300 --> 00:07:00.750
So if you want to take that
into consideration, you might.

00:07:00.750 --> 00:07:05.380
But it depends as much
on you as the students.

00:07:05.380 --> 00:07:09.130
If you're going to be
really tired at 4:00

00:07:09.130 --> 00:07:11.980
but they're just waking up,
then don't teach it at 4:00.

00:07:11.980 --> 00:07:15.410
Maybe don't teach at 4:00.

00:07:15.410 --> 00:07:18.360
And the last one was
guiding readings.

00:07:18.360 --> 00:07:20.751
If you just put a
lot of readings up,

00:07:20.751 --> 00:07:23.000
students might not know where
to focus their attention

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:24.470
until after the class.

00:07:24.470 --> 00:07:28.910
So there are reading
questions, reading guides

00:07:28.910 --> 00:07:30.170
that you can post.

00:07:30.170 --> 00:07:32.180
Read such and such
and try and think

00:07:32.180 --> 00:07:34.730
about how you might explain
this, that, or the other thing.

00:07:34.730 --> 00:07:37.370
And then there's also
pre-class questions

00:07:37.370 --> 00:07:39.380
you can ask that
they might derive,

00:07:39.380 --> 00:07:43.110
that they may have to pull
from the readings to answer.

00:07:43.110 --> 00:07:48.310
So the concept of just in
time teaching, the idea

00:07:48.310 --> 00:07:50.720
that students do
a reading and then

00:07:50.720 --> 00:07:52.970
they actually have to answer
questions on the reading

00:07:52.970 --> 00:07:56.060
before they come to class
and submit their answers.

00:07:56.060 --> 00:07:58.610
So there's a whole
procedure around that.

00:07:58.610 --> 00:07:59.990
It can be very, very effective.

00:07:59.990 --> 00:08:01.406
You can do it for a large class.

00:08:01.406 --> 00:08:02.780
There's strategies
and techniques

00:08:02.780 --> 00:08:05.270
to streamline the amount
of time you put into it.

00:08:05.270 --> 00:08:07.730
But it does force them
to do the reading.

00:08:07.730 --> 00:08:11.830
And it does guide, at some
level, what they read.

00:08:11.830 --> 00:08:13.580
And that's a great
great approach.

00:08:13.580 --> 00:08:18.620
And I'm happy to talk more about
that at another time or later

00:08:18.620 --> 00:08:21.590
or offline.

