00:49:51.830 --> 00:49:54.350
of learning, measuring
how much students learn,

00:49:54.350 --> 00:49:56.990
and then how much they retain
and all that kind of stuff.

00:49:56.990 --> 00:49:59.240
And when you go
through that, students

00:49:59.240 --> 00:50:03.710
seem to learn more and retain
more in the active learning

00:50:03.710 --> 00:50:06.770
format, even though they
really at least half of them

00:50:06.770 --> 00:50:08.010
don't like it at all.

00:50:08.010 --> 00:50:10.920
So it's an
interesting commentary

00:50:10.920 --> 00:50:12.410
That's a good great story.

00:50:12.410 --> 00:50:13.993
So why don't you
give the ball a toss?

00:50:16.760 --> 00:50:17.505
There you go.

00:50:20.190 --> 00:50:22.010
No, you have to
answer a question.

00:50:22.010 --> 00:50:24.560
Have you ever experienced
active learning

00:50:24.560 --> 00:50:26.270
in a classroom
besides this class?

00:50:26.270 --> 00:50:29.510
And how did it work or not work?

00:50:29.510 --> 00:50:31.580
AUDIENCE: I would
say yes to that.

00:50:31.580 --> 00:50:35.347
It's definitely the traditional
method, sitting in front,

00:50:35.347 --> 00:50:36.780
face to face lecture.

00:50:39.437 --> 00:50:40.520
JANET RANKIN: Fair enough.

00:50:40.520 --> 00:50:41.695
Give a toss, toss to anyone.

00:50:45.840 --> 00:50:48.770
Are we going to get the
same answer from all of you?

00:50:48.770 --> 00:50:50.044
If it's just--

00:50:50.044 --> 00:50:51.460
AUDIENCE: Is it
the same question?

00:50:51.460 --> 00:50:53.840
JANET RANKIN: Yeah,
same question.

00:50:53.840 --> 00:50:56.638
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I have.

00:50:56.638 --> 00:50:59.720
Because I recently
studied in Sweden.

00:50:59.720 --> 00:51:03.000
And that's the way, most
of the time that way,

00:51:03.000 --> 00:51:03.970
they teach in Sweden.

00:51:03.970 --> 00:51:10.494
So for some classes, generally
in higher level classes,

00:51:10.494 --> 00:51:13.910
according with d-level classes,
they use active learning.

00:51:13.910 --> 00:51:17.870
JANET RANKIN: Great and
students buy into it?

00:51:17.870 --> 00:51:18.730
They're OK with it?

00:51:18.730 --> 00:51:21.034
They work at it?

00:51:21.034 --> 00:51:23.472
AUDIENCE: Culturally,
they tend to veer

00:51:23.472 --> 00:51:24.472
towards active learning.

00:51:27.117 --> 00:51:29.200
JANET RANKIN: And that's
a very interesting point,

00:51:29.200 --> 00:51:34.801
the idea that it can
be a cultural thing.

00:51:34.801 --> 00:51:37.660
If everybody else is doing
it, or it's expected,

00:51:37.660 --> 00:51:39.070
then that's what you do right.

00:51:39.070 --> 00:51:43.210
So some of these changes,
there's an incubation period

00:51:43.210 --> 00:51:46.427
before they actually take off
and they're widely accepted.

00:51:46.427 --> 00:51:47.968
AUDIENCE: In fact
in Denmark, I think

00:51:47.968 --> 00:51:50.805
that's the only way they each.

00:51:50.805 --> 00:51:52.180
JANET RANKIN: It's
pretty active.

00:51:52.180 --> 00:51:54.860
I have a colleague
who's in, or friend

00:51:54.860 --> 00:51:58.600
who works at the
University of Copenhagen,

00:51:58.600 --> 00:52:03.670
and all new faculty have to take
a yearlong course on teaching,

00:52:03.670 --> 00:52:07.690
no matter what department,
physics, math, a year long,

00:52:07.690 --> 00:52:08.530
the faculty.

00:52:08.530 --> 00:52:13.030
And here you could never force
the faculty to do anything.

00:52:13.030 --> 00:52:14.770
So it's pretty
interesting that they've

00:52:14.770 --> 00:52:16.140
been doing it for so long.

00:52:16.140 --> 00:52:17.765
AUDIENCE: I have a
question about that.

00:52:17.765 --> 00:52:24.106
Is it the way that professors,
their role as actual teachers

00:52:24.106 --> 00:52:25.097
is viewed?

00:52:25.097 --> 00:52:25.597
[INAUDIBLE]

00:52:25.597 --> 00:52:27.088
But seriously,
people [INAUDIBLE]

00:52:27.088 --> 00:52:30.402
or something, I think definitely
trying to enforce a teaching

00:52:30.402 --> 00:52:31.860
class would be a
lot more receptive

00:52:31.860 --> 00:52:35.290
than if you tried to enforce
that here, where teaching

00:52:35.290 --> 00:52:38.210
isn't necessarily the focus.

00:52:38.210 --> 00:52:42.890
JANET RANKIN: But there, it's
a good research university.

00:52:42.890 --> 00:52:45.732
But on the teaching
side, that's the norm.

00:52:45.732 --> 00:52:46.690
That's the expectation.

00:52:46.690 --> 00:52:47.690
AUDIENCE: But what
about requiring--

00:52:47.690 --> 00:52:49.190
I know it's hard when
you have professors

00:52:49.190 --> 00:52:50.564
that have been
doing what they're

00:52:50.564 --> 00:52:53.026
doing for 25, 30, 40 years.

00:52:53.026 --> 00:52:54.942
It's hard to get them
to adopt new techniques.

00:52:54.942 --> 00:52:57.796
But I think that requiring
things-- the faculty

00:52:57.796 --> 00:53:01.212
that you can require things
of are the new faculty, who

00:53:01.212 --> 00:53:03.650
have no power yet.

00:53:03.650 --> 00:53:05.360
JANET RANKIN: Yes and no.

00:53:05.360 --> 00:53:08.450
If the tenured system, the
requirements for tenure

00:53:08.450 --> 00:53:13.700
don't change, then asking
them to take on new-- oh,

00:53:13.700 --> 00:53:15.410
you guys should try
active learning.

00:53:15.410 --> 00:53:16.670
Revamp this course.

00:53:16.670 --> 00:53:18.980
And then they don't get tenure.

00:53:18.980 --> 00:53:21.740
So it really has to be
a whole systemic change,

00:53:21.740 --> 00:53:24.680
where the department buys in.

00:53:24.680 --> 00:53:26.180
The school buys in.

00:53:26.180 --> 00:53:27.950
The university buys
in and says, OK, these

00:53:27.950 --> 00:53:29.750
are the criteria for tenure.

00:53:29.750 --> 00:53:34.070
And in that is you have
to use active learning.

00:53:34.070 --> 00:53:35.210
Or you have to--

00:53:35.210 --> 00:53:36.960
that's where it would
have to get change.

00:53:36.960 --> 00:53:38.780
Otherwise you
can't expect people

00:53:38.780 --> 00:53:40.460
that aren't tenured to do it.

00:53:40.460 --> 00:53:41.780
You shouldn't.

00:53:41.780 --> 00:53:43.250
Let's give the
ball one more toss.

00:53:50.570 --> 00:53:53.316
AUDIENCE: So it's
been a long time

00:53:53.316 --> 00:53:54.618
since I've been in a classroom.

00:53:54.618 --> 00:53:59.010
I would say, in a
regular classroom,

00:53:59.010 --> 00:54:01.286
I don't that I've
been in a class that

00:54:01.286 --> 00:54:02.350
does active learning.

00:54:02.350 --> 00:54:08.309
But I have taken courses
that are largely lab courses,

00:54:08.309 --> 00:54:09.850
like a mouse embryology
course, where

00:54:09.850 --> 00:54:14.896
you have 15 minutes of lecture.

00:54:14.896 --> 00:54:17.190
And then you go into
the lab And you do it.

00:54:17.190 --> 00:54:19.479
And the professor will
walk around and help you

00:54:19.479 --> 00:54:20.270
with the technique.

00:54:20.270 --> 00:54:21.770
You're actually
there with the mice.

00:54:21.770 --> 00:54:24.160
And you're actually
doing something.

00:54:24.160 --> 00:54:26.750
So does that count?

00:54:26.750 --> 00:54:31.430
JANET RANKIN: Lab courses
can be their own genre.

00:54:31.430 --> 00:54:34.310
But there has been
this movement to take

00:54:34.310 --> 00:54:39.130
that's a little bit of what TEAL
does, at a more simple level.

00:54:39.130 --> 00:54:40.820
And there's a little
bit of lecture.

00:54:40.820 --> 00:54:43.111
And then students are supposed
to answer some questions

00:54:43.111 --> 00:54:44.240
or do something.

00:54:44.240 --> 00:54:46.280
And then they come
back together.

00:54:46.280 --> 00:54:49.880
And Studio Labs at WPI
has that same format,

00:54:49.880 --> 00:54:53.600
where the classrooms are
built with lab benches.

00:54:53.600 --> 00:54:57.710
And students sit at lab
benches and see a lecture.

00:54:57.710 --> 00:55:00.110
And then they do
some experiments.

00:55:00.110 --> 00:55:01.310
They're mini experiments.

00:55:01.310 --> 00:55:07.190
It's not whole mouse dissection.

00:55:07.190 --> 00:55:09.140
But they do a mini experiment.

00:55:09.140 --> 00:55:10.700
And then they report back.

00:55:10.700 --> 00:55:12.530
And there's an
interchange like that.

00:55:12.530 --> 00:55:17.330
So there are some
blending of the two.

00:55:17.330 --> 00:55:20.390
Often what people do
in labs is different.

00:55:20.390 --> 00:55:23.405
And usually a good
lab is fabulous.

00:55:23.405 --> 00:55:26.120
A good lab is fabulous, which
is another argument for why

00:55:26.120 --> 00:55:28.394
active learning is
good, because everybody

00:55:28.394 --> 00:55:30.560
thinks back about, oh, that
lab course was so great.

00:55:30.560 --> 00:55:32.040
I learned so much
and did so much.

00:55:32.040 --> 00:55:33.980
And yet that's the lab course.

00:55:33.980 --> 00:55:35.220
And then we have the lecture.

00:55:35.220 --> 00:55:40.440
So it's an interesting comment.

00:55:40.440 --> 00:55:42.200
So that was the beach ball.

00:55:42.200 --> 00:55:44.090
And you see you
guys got to throw

00:55:44.090 --> 00:55:45.890
the ball at other students.

00:55:45.890 --> 00:55:48.290
So I didn't have
to pick on every--

00:55:48.290 --> 00:55:50.420
I didn't have to call on
people or pick on people.

00:55:53.510 --> 00:55:56.390
I had a little demo here
about why it's important,

00:55:56.390 --> 00:56:01.280
just if you ask a question
or you ask students

00:56:01.280 --> 00:56:04.629
if there are any questions
or what questions they have.

00:56:04.629 --> 00:56:06.170
And that's generally
a better phrase.

00:56:06.170 --> 00:56:08.330
What questions do you have?

00:56:08.330 --> 00:56:11.900
It's more welcoming, opposed to
saying OK, who's stupid enough.

00:56:11.900 --> 00:56:15.010
Who's not following me?

00:56:15.010 --> 00:56:17.980
Say, OK, what are the questions?

00:56:17.980 --> 00:56:20.540
It's a more welcoming phrase.

00:56:20.540 --> 00:56:23.300
But the idea of waiting.

00:56:23.300 --> 00:56:26.000
So here, if I click
on this little guy,

00:56:26.000 --> 00:56:31.380
you should hear 30
seconds of music.

00:56:31.380 --> 00:56:33.890
So imagine you ask a question,
30 seconds for people

00:56:33.890 --> 00:56:36.210
to think about it and
formulate an answer.

00:56:36.210 --> 00:56:41.240
This is what 30 seconds
feels like of dead time.

00:56:41.240 --> 00:56:43.098
Well, there'll be music.

00:56:43.098 --> 00:56:46.062
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:57:07.259 --> 00:57:08.175
That's not part of it.

00:57:15.734 --> 00:57:17.150
So did that feel
like a long time?

00:57:17.150 --> 00:57:20.270
I know we had a
little break there.

00:57:20.270 --> 00:57:22.580
But that feels like a lot.

00:57:22.580 --> 00:57:24.650
Especially when you're
standing up here,

00:57:24.650 --> 00:57:25.970
it feels like a long time.

00:57:25.970 --> 00:57:30.260
But 30 seconds, give
them 30 seconds.

00:57:30.260 --> 00:57:32.767
The point is, if you want
to give students 30 seconds,

00:57:32.767 --> 00:57:34.100
you're going to have to time it.

00:57:34.100 --> 00:57:37.010
You totally have to time it,
because you will not estimate

00:57:37.010 --> 00:57:38.990
30 seconds effectively.

00:57:38.990 --> 00:57:41.750
You will totally
underestimate it.

00:57:41.750 --> 00:57:44.420
And then another
technique that you

00:57:44.420 --> 00:57:47.450
can piggyback on that is
saying, OK, take 30 seconds.

00:57:47.450 --> 00:57:51.170
I'm not going to take any
answers for 30 seconds.

00:57:51.170 --> 00:57:52.790
So you may have an
answer right away.

00:57:52.790 --> 00:57:54.590
But I don't want to
hear it for 30 seconds,

00:57:54.590 --> 00:57:56.465
because there's always
that guy in the front.

00:57:56.465 --> 00:57:59.060
I had this guy in my
high school math class.

00:57:59.060 --> 00:58:01.540
And he used to sit on his--
this little short guy--

00:58:01.540 --> 00:58:03.821
and he used to sit on
his foot on the chair.

00:58:03.821 --> 00:58:04.570
He's on his chair.

00:58:04.570 --> 00:58:05.750
And he's sitting on his foot.

00:58:05.750 --> 00:58:06.740
And he had his hand like this.

00:58:06.740 --> 00:58:07.910
And he was in the front row.

00:58:07.910 --> 00:58:11.870
And whenever the teacher asked
the question, he would go.

00:58:11.870 --> 00:58:14.079
And he would come up off of it.

00:58:14.079 --> 00:58:16.370
And so he was always the guy
that answer the questions.

00:58:16.370 --> 00:58:21.452
But that left some of us
who took a little more time

00:58:21.452 --> 00:58:22.910
not having the
opportunity, kind of

00:58:22.910 --> 00:58:27.090
like having the one person write
all the time in the TEAL group.

00:58:27.090 --> 00:58:31.830
So that's a good way
to go about that.

00:58:31.830 --> 00:58:34.910
We talk a little bit about
using clicker questions

00:58:34.910 --> 00:58:35.770
to solicit feedback.

00:58:35.770 --> 00:58:37.520
And we've used the
plickers in this class.

00:58:37.520 --> 00:58:40.430
We'll use them again.

00:58:40.430 --> 00:58:44.280
You can get dedicated
clickers, these dedicated punch

00:58:44.280 --> 00:58:44.870
in things.

00:58:44.870 --> 00:58:47.492
They use them for TEAL, I think.

00:58:47.492 --> 00:58:48.950
Students may have
to purchase them.

00:58:48.950 --> 00:58:49.790
That may cost money.

00:58:49.790 --> 00:58:51.498
The department may
have to purchase them.

00:58:51.498 --> 00:58:53.202
That's another source of money.

00:58:53.202 --> 00:58:55.720
AUDIENCE: They make
us buy everything.

00:58:55.720 --> 00:59:00.520
JANET RANKIN: So when I
was at Brown, actually,

00:59:00.520 --> 00:59:01.770
the department would buy them.

00:59:01.770 --> 00:59:03.360
And they'd leave
them in the library.

00:59:03.360 --> 00:59:06.120
And then you could check them
out with your student ID.

00:59:06.120 --> 00:59:07.550
And then you got that.

00:59:07.550 --> 00:59:09.090
So you got it for the semester.

00:59:09.090 --> 00:59:10.050
But it was linked to your ID.

00:59:10.050 --> 00:59:12.466
And if you didn't bring it
back, they'd charge you for it.

00:59:12.466 --> 00:59:16.840
But that's another way to do
it, a fairer way to do it.

00:59:16.840 --> 00:59:20.195
We'll look at something
called Socrative later on.

00:59:20.195 --> 00:59:21.070
I'll use it later on.

00:59:21.070 --> 00:59:22.410
But it's a text.

00:59:22.410 --> 00:59:23.860
It's an online format.

00:59:23.860 --> 00:59:27.030
So students need a
smartphone or a laptop.

00:59:27.030 --> 00:59:29.490
But they don't need
a separate clicker.

00:59:29.490 --> 00:59:32.550
There are issues with that,
because not everybody is

00:59:32.550 --> 00:59:33.780
going to have a smartphone.

00:59:33.780 --> 00:59:37.590
And are you biasing your class
against people that don't

00:59:37.590 --> 00:59:40.320
happen to have the technology?

00:59:40.320 --> 00:59:42.510
This is why I like
plickers, because you

00:59:42.510 --> 00:59:43.890
don't need to buy anything.

00:59:43.890 --> 00:59:45.090
I give you the card.

00:59:45.090 --> 00:59:48.330
And I need to have
the smartphone.

00:59:48.330 --> 00:59:49.980
But you don't.

00:59:49.980 --> 00:59:51.900
And then you could
always use index cards

00:59:51.900 --> 00:59:54.570
or do the whole,
put one finger up

00:59:54.570 --> 00:59:57.480
if you think it's A and two
if it's B and three if it's

00:59:57.480 --> 01:00:01.050
C. That gets a little
tough in a bigger class,

01:00:01.050 --> 01:00:02.550
because it's hard to see.

01:00:02.550 --> 01:00:04.710
It's hard to count.

01:00:04.710 --> 01:00:08.160
I like the fact that
the clickers, plickers,

01:00:08.160 --> 01:00:09.990
and the Socrative
or Poll Everywhere

01:00:09.990 --> 01:00:11.290
give you a histogram.

01:00:11.290 --> 01:00:14.330
So you get a really quick
idea about who's getting it

01:00:14.330 --> 01:00:17.566
and who isn't getting it.

01:00:17.566 --> 01:00:19.190
So we're going to do
a couple of these.

01:00:19.190 --> 01:00:21.950
Remember-- this is from
the label of the free body

01:00:21.950 --> 01:00:28.640
diagram-- that these
misconceptions always

01:00:28.640 --> 01:00:30.500
linger in a lecture class.

01:00:30.500 --> 01:00:34.940
We talked about this free
diagram the other day.

01:00:34.940 --> 01:00:38.240
So let's just try this one here,
give you another little warm up

01:00:38.240 --> 01:00:39.320
on the picker's.

01:00:39.320 --> 01:00:40.640
So you have the card.

01:00:40.640 --> 01:00:47.290
And I'm just going to ask
you to look at the question.

01:00:47.290 --> 01:00:52.180
And when you're ready to
answer, just hold up your card.

01:00:52.180 --> 01:01:00.020
And if you can keep your
finger away from the pattern,

01:01:00.020 --> 01:01:05.000
that would be great, because
it makes it hard to read it.

01:01:05.000 --> 01:01:06.360
And then however you want to--

01:01:14.932 --> 01:01:16.890
AUDIENCE: Does this work
for larger classrooms?

01:01:16.890 --> 01:01:18.300
JANET RANKIN: It does.

01:01:18.300 --> 01:01:20.490
I have a colleague
who uses it at Brown.

01:01:20.490 --> 01:01:22.950
And he just started
teaching this semester.

01:01:22.950 --> 01:01:24.610
And he showed me his--

01:01:24.610 --> 01:01:28.560
or a friend-- he
showed me his plickers.

01:01:28.560 --> 01:01:32.460
And he printed them
out on 8 by 10,

01:01:32.460 --> 01:01:35.220
like a sheet of
paper, cardstock.

01:01:35.220 --> 01:01:37.380
And they're enormous.

01:01:37.380 --> 01:01:39.540
They're like this big.

01:01:39.540 --> 01:01:41.951
AUDIENCE: How do you
not get [INAUDIBLE]?

01:01:41.951 --> 01:01:43.450
Well Well they have
to hold them up.

01:01:43.450 --> 01:01:44.040
You have to.

01:01:44.040 --> 01:01:45.581
And you can walk
around a little bit.

01:01:45.581 --> 01:01:47.320
But I'll show you this.

01:01:47.320 --> 01:01:48.990
So I have the histogram.

01:01:48.990 --> 01:01:53.100
And I measured everybody.

01:01:53.100 --> 01:01:56.100
So now I know what you
think about this question.

01:01:56.100 --> 01:01:57.677
I know who's got it right.

01:01:57.677 --> 01:01:59.010
I don't know who's got it right.

01:01:59.010 --> 01:02:12.260
But I know that most of you
have chosen the correct answer.

01:02:12.260 --> 01:02:17.220
But there were a
few of you picked up

01:02:17.220 --> 01:02:18.790
one of the other answers.

01:02:18.790 --> 01:02:23.440
And so now I know that it's a
non-trivial number of you that

01:02:23.440 --> 01:02:26.000
picked an incorrect answer.

01:02:26.000 --> 01:02:29.950
So now I know exactly
what I need to do.

01:02:29.950 --> 01:02:31.690
It's given me incredibly
good information

01:02:31.690 --> 01:02:33.160
that there is some
out there that

01:02:33.160 --> 01:02:36.640
have a pretty strong
misunderstanding

01:02:36.640 --> 01:02:38.920
of the literature.

01:02:38.920 --> 01:02:40.420
And that's that
some of you picked

01:02:40.420 --> 01:02:48.070
A. There's a lot of data to
support that active learning,

01:02:48.070 --> 01:02:50.746
active technique supports
student learning.

01:02:50.746 --> 01:02:52.495
I call your attention
to the Freeman paper

01:02:52.495 --> 01:02:55.810
