01:06:55.360 --> 01:06:59.570
plickers, whatever, takes
a three step process.

01:06:59.570 --> 01:07:01.150
One is that people
generally start

01:07:01.150 --> 01:07:04.660
with these simple
fact questions,

01:07:04.660 --> 01:07:07.200
and then more challenging
conceptual questions, which

01:07:07.200 --> 01:07:10.720
I would put the
one we just did at.

01:07:10.720 --> 01:07:12.700
That students, they might--

01:07:12.700 --> 01:07:16.450
arguing with each
other could be useful.

01:07:16.450 --> 01:07:18.490
And then the third
is you've just

01:07:18.490 --> 01:07:20.080
totally revamped the lecture.

01:07:20.080 --> 01:07:21.980
And it's all centered
around these questions.

01:07:21.980 --> 01:07:23.740
And depending on
how students answer,

01:07:23.740 --> 01:07:27.460
that's how you navigate
through the lecture

01:07:27.460 --> 01:07:29.860
or through the
course, class period.

01:07:29.860 --> 01:07:33.210
I would never recommend that
anybody start with this one.

01:07:33.210 --> 01:07:36.190
I think that we're all capable
of starting with two actually.

01:07:36.190 --> 01:07:39.610
And I think starting with
three may be a waste of time,

01:07:39.610 --> 01:07:41.860
unless you really just want
to check and see if people

01:07:41.860 --> 01:07:42.770
did the reading or something.

01:07:42.770 --> 01:07:43.280
It's a big class.

01:07:43.280 --> 01:07:45.488
And you just want to see if
they've done the reading.

01:07:45.488 --> 01:07:47.912
But in general, I would
say put your energy

01:07:47.912 --> 01:07:49.870
into coming up with some
really good questions.

01:07:49.870 --> 01:07:51.040
And maybe don't ask as many.

01:07:53.740 --> 01:07:56.890
And then as I keep
saying, I hope

01:07:56.890 --> 01:08:00.257
