01:12:06.410 --> 01:12:08.870
And everybody else just file
in and go opposite someone.

01:12:14.910 --> 01:12:16.370
Sarah, do you want
to participate?

01:12:21.450 --> 01:12:23.530
So here's what happens.

01:12:23.530 --> 01:12:24.930
I'm going to tell you to go.

01:12:24.930 --> 01:12:27.000
And you have two minutes.

01:12:27.000 --> 01:12:31.200
The person in this line
takes some amount of time

01:12:31.200 --> 01:12:36.420
and says what their answer
is and why they chose it.

01:12:36.420 --> 01:12:39.150
And the person in that line
can ask questions or whatever,

01:12:39.150 --> 01:12:42.215
and then say what they thought
and say why they thought that.

01:12:42.215 --> 01:12:44.340
So you're going to have a
really quick conversation

01:12:44.340 --> 01:12:46.770
about your choices.

01:12:46.770 --> 01:12:50.790
And after two minutes, I'm going
to tell you to please stop.

01:12:50.790 --> 01:12:54.870
And then you have
to get a new person.

01:12:54.870 --> 01:12:56.520
And I'll show you
how to do that.

01:12:56.520 --> 01:12:58.380
Everybody understand
what we're doing?

01:12:58.380 --> 01:13:00.840
You're having a two
minute exchange of ideas.

01:13:00.840 --> 01:13:02.970
And it's going to be loud.

01:13:02.970 --> 01:13:03.500
Believe me.

01:13:03.500 --> 01:13:05.265
And it's the person
opposite you.

01:13:09.590 --> 01:13:11.330
Are you ready?

01:13:11.330 --> 01:13:13.450
Everyone ready?

01:13:13.450 --> 01:13:19.030
On your mark, get set, go.

01:13:19.030 --> 01:13:21.230
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

01:13:45.594 --> 01:13:46.510
Let me ask a question.

01:13:46.510 --> 01:13:49.860
Did you encounter people that
had different choices than you?

01:13:49.860 --> 01:13:50.500
AUDIENCE: Yes.

01:13:50.500 --> 01:13:53.350
JANET RANKIN: Yes.

01:13:53.350 --> 01:13:58.360
So that generally means
it's a pretty good question,

01:13:58.360 --> 01:14:00.760
because you get to hear lots
of different perspectives.

01:14:00.760 --> 01:14:05.050
Now if this were the central
part of the class, this topic,

01:14:05.050 --> 01:14:08.680
you might let the pairings
go even longer, even more

01:14:08.680 --> 01:14:10.240
pairings.

01:14:10.240 --> 01:14:13.090
So did anybody change
their mind based on what

01:14:13.090 --> 01:14:14.545
they heard a partner say?

01:14:17.260 --> 01:14:20.002
OK, a couple of you.

01:14:20.002 --> 01:14:21.460
Generally, what
happens then is you

01:14:21.460 --> 01:14:23.860
would want to have
a de-brief, where

01:14:23.860 --> 01:14:27.040
we talk about why you
picked the answer you picked

01:14:27.040 --> 01:14:28.810
and what you picked.

01:14:28.810 --> 01:14:31.180
And most of the
time, the choices

01:14:31.180 --> 01:14:32.950
are a little been informative.

01:14:32.950 --> 01:14:36.970
If you found, as the instructor,
that everybody picked

01:14:36.970 --> 01:14:40.420
a negative number, well you're
in a very different place

01:14:40.420 --> 01:14:44.920
than if people are arguing
over how much positive it is.

01:14:44.920 --> 01:14:46.630
So you're going to
use that information

01:14:46.630 --> 01:14:52.340
to find out about where
the misconceptions are.

01:14:52.340 --> 01:14:54.216
What's the advantage
of this method?

01:14:58.522 --> 01:14:59.384
Gordon.

01:14:59.384 --> 01:15:02.003
AUDIENCE: It's very
interesting, I thought.

