01:15:05.044 --> 01:15:07.529
We never talk to each other.

01:15:07.529 --> 01:15:12.002
And it's easier for
them as to [INAUDIBLE].

01:15:12.002 --> 01:15:16.105
So at the beginning, they
are aware of conflicts.

01:15:16.105 --> 01:15:19.556
But as we rotated,
there was a convergence.

01:15:19.556 --> 01:15:22.514
It was very interesting.

01:15:22.514 --> 01:15:25.965
JANET RANKIN: [INAUDIBLE]
have your hand up.

01:15:25.965 --> 01:15:30.410
AUDIENCE: Yes, one time
I was laughing just

01:15:30.410 --> 01:15:32.330
because it was very effective.

01:15:32.330 --> 01:15:34.903
There was so much [INAUDIBLE].

01:15:34.903 --> 01:15:39.020
And when we started,
one resisted

01:15:39.020 --> 01:15:42.620
some passionated idea about
this is how it should be.

01:15:42.620 --> 01:15:44.370
And by the time it
went to all the people,

01:15:44.370 --> 01:15:46.860
people can get all the idea.

01:15:46.860 --> 01:15:48.880
You try to look for
the superior idea.

01:15:48.880 --> 01:15:52.410
Then you decide,
oh, this is better.

01:15:52.410 --> 01:15:56.933
When we try to switch again,
you listen to a better argument.

01:15:59.630 --> 01:16:02.298
So from which one decides
without [INAUDIBLE]

01:16:02.298 --> 01:16:03.170
the first one?

01:16:05.615 --> 01:16:06.990
JANET RANKIN: A
couple of points.

01:16:06.990 --> 01:16:11.190
One is that it's impossible not
to-- when you pair people up,

01:16:11.190 --> 01:16:16.190
it's pretty hard for
somebody not to participate.

01:16:16.190 --> 01:16:18.000
So if you have somebody
that's resistant,

01:16:18.000 --> 01:16:19.250
they might still be resistant.

01:16:19.250 --> 01:16:21.914
But it's virtually impossible
for them not to participate.

01:16:21.914 --> 01:16:23.330
And also it's a
little less scary.

01:16:23.330 --> 01:16:24.710
One person, it's really noisy.

01:16:24.710 --> 01:16:27.168
You know you only have to talk
to them for a minute or two.

01:16:27.168 --> 01:16:28.790
So it's a little less scary.

01:16:28.790 --> 01:16:30.950
Everybody's doing it.

01:16:30.950 --> 01:16:33.800
The other thing is that
you definitely want

01:16:33.800 --> 01:16:35.660
to have some sort of de-brief.

01:16:35.660 --> 01:16:38.002
You can't just stop and
go, OK, let's go on.

01:16:38.002 --> 01:16:40.460
You're going to have to find
out what people's answers are.

01:16:40.460 --> 01:16:43.190
And you're going to have to
address it or at least reveal

01:16:43.190 --> 01:16:46.220
the right answer, because
there's many places

01:16:46.220 --> 01:16:49.730
many, many places
for misconception.

01:16:49.730 --> 01:16:52.160
And also, then, if
you do it enough,

01:16:52.160 --> 01:16:54.260
you can maybe--
students can find

01:16:54.260 --> 01:16:57.200
arguments or people's
explanations that

01:16:57.200 --> 01:16:58.520
resonate with them.

01:16:58.520 --> 01:17:02.870
And then you get exposed to
different kinds of arguments

01:17:02.870 --> 01:17:05.760
or different kinds of ways
of explaining the problem.

01:17:05.760 --> 01:17:11.540
So in this case, the answer is
actually positive 0.4 degrees.

01:17:11.540 --> 01:17:18.334
So B is the correct
answer, just so you know.

01:17:18.334 --> 01:17:19.750
AUDIENCE: Yes, I
