method could be confusing

01:17:23.100 --> 01:17:23.770
as well.

01:17:23.770 --> 01:17:27.102
For instance, if you listen
to two superior arguments,

01:17:27.102 --> 01:17:28.250
one against.

01:17:28.250 --> 01:17:31.840
For instance, I talked to
someone who was actually

01:17:31.840 --> 01:17:34.155
in support of negative.

01:17:34.155 --> 01:17:37.944
And she brought an argument
and so forth like that.

01:17:37.944 --> 01:17:39.625
And somebody
thought of positive.

01:17:39.625 --> 01:17:42.210
And there was a strong
argument also for that.

01:17:42.210 --> 01:17:44.601
Sometimes if you just
be sitting on the fence,

01:17:44.601 --> 01:17:45.850
I don't know where to get off.

01:17:45.850 --> 01:17:48.670
JANET RANKIN: Well I think it's
OK to be confused for a while.

01:17:48.670 --> 01:17:49.900
That's fine.

01:17:49.900 --> 01:17:52.150
As I said, if this were a
course on global warming,

01:17:52.150 --> 01:17:55.810
climate change, whatever it
is, we would have to make sure

01:17:55.810 --> 01:17:57.940
that we heard all of
those explanations

01:17:57.940 --> 01:18:00.250
or a sampling of those
explanations and said,

01:18:00.250 --> 01:18:02.470
oh, well that's a good.

01:18:02.470 --> 01:18:03.700
I can see why you think that.

01:18:03.700 --> 01:18:06.370
But you've forgotten about this.

01:18:06.370 --> 01:18:09.100
Or I can see why, so
that you can process it

01:18:09.100 --> 01:18:11.990
all so that people
don't leave confused.

01:18:11.990 --> 01:18:14.479
But it's good to hear
the wrong answer,

01:18:14.479 --> 01:18:16.270
to be convinced of the
wrong answer, maybe,

01:18:16.270 --> 01:18:19.920
but then to see why it's wrong.

01:18:19.920 --> 01:18:22.590
That's an important
learning activity.

01:18:22.590 --> 01:18:25.867
AUDIENCE: But this
method is only

01:18:25.867 --> 01:18:29.703
applicable for where you have
cases where you can debate.

01:18:29.703 --> 01:18:33.160
Because if you have very clear
cases, for example, if I ask,

01:18:33.160 --> 01:18:37.830
what is the color of the sky?

01:18:37.830 --> 01:18:38.790
It's a definite.

01:18:38.790 --> 01:18:42.390
But when it's fuzzy,
then this can be--

01:18:42.390 --> 01:18:44.530
JANET RANKIN: Yes, or
when it's a concept

01:18:44.530 --> 01:18:47.620
you think people might
have difficulty with.

01:18:47.620 --> 01:18:52.890
Yeah, it's not going to work
if it's a real clear cut.

01:18:52.890 --> 01:18:55.890
I want to demo one more method.

01:18:55.890 --> 01:18:59.120
This is think, pair, share.

01:18:59.120 --> 01:19:01.100
And I know we've been
doing those forever.

01:19:01.100 --> 01:19:06.155
But I'm going to couple it
with a clicker question.

01:19:06.155 --> 01:19:10.790
And I think we can do
it in seven minutes.

01:19:10.790 --> 01:19:11.390
So

01:19:11.390 --> 01:19:15.110
I have two blocks here, because
this is just too fun, really.

01:19:15.110 --> 01:19:16.956
I have two blocks.

01:19:16.956 --> 01:19:19.740
They're the same
width and the same.

01:19:19.740 --> 01:19:22.710
Length but they are
different thickness.

01:19:22.710 --> 01:19:25.070
And I have this thing.

01:19:25.070 --> 01:19:27.780
And I'm going to tap
on the thin block.

01:19:31.620 --> 01:19:33.872
Makes more or less--

01:19:33.872 --> 01:19:34.830
it's not really a note.

01:19:34.830 --> 01:19:38.010
But it's some sound.

01:19:38.010 --> 01:19:39.960
And I'm going to
ask you, when I do

01:19:39.960 --> 01:19:46.290
the same thing, the same
force, the same place

01:19:46.290 --> 01:19:49.380
on the thick block, will
the note be higher, lower,

01:19:49.380 --> 01:19:53.970
or the same as the thin block?

01:19:53.970 --> 01:19:57.720
And this should be A, B, and
C, not one two and three.

01:19:57.720 --> 01:19:59.520
So but if it's A,
B, and C go ahead

01:19:59.520 --> 01:20:01.245
and vote with your plickers.

01:20:04.115 --> 01:20:05.990
Do you know that's what
they auto correct to?

01:20:05.990 --> 01:20:09.340
That's what it, if you're
typing and you write plickers,

01:20:09.340 --> 01:20:11.780
it autocorrects
to pluckers, which

01:20:11.780 --> 01:20:13.250
can be pretty embarrassing.

01:20:13.250 --> 01:20:17.190
AUDIENCE: So high
is for A. You've not

01:20:17.190 --> 01:20:20.330
clicked on the thicker one.

01:20:20.330 --> 01:20:21.380
JANET RANKIN: I know.

01:20:21.380 --> 01:20:25.084
That's why you have to tell
me what you think it is.

01:20:25.084 --> 01:20:26.930
AUDIENCE: Is this a A, B, and C?

01:20:26.930 --> 01:20:29.570
JANET RANKIN: A B
and C. So there's

01:20:29.570 --> 01:20:33.740
no D. There's a reason for this.

01:20:33.740 --> 01:20:36.639
If I told you the
answer, then there

01:20:36.639 --> 01:20:37.930
wouldn't be much fun in voting.

01:20:45.770 --> 01:20:48.890
And I have everybody.

01:20:48.890 --> 01:20:51.609
So I have a distribution.

01:20:51.609 --> 01:20:53.400
I'm not going to tell
you the distribution.

01:20:53.400 --> 01:20:56.500
I'm not going to share that
with you I'd like you to take--

01:20:56.500 --> 01:20:58.250
just cluster.

01:20:58.250 --> 01:21:02.330
It could be groups of three or
four, whenever you have nearby,

01:21:02.330 --> 01:21:06.369
and talk about why you
picked the answer you picked.

01:21:06.369 --> 01:21:08.910
And then I'm going to give you
the opportunity to vote again.

01:21:08.910 --> 01:21:12.890
So in the interest of time,
two minutes to discuss this.

01:21:12.890 --> 01:21:15.390
[SIDE CONVERSATIONS]

01:21:36.080 --> 01:21:39.650
I wanted to just call attention
to a couple things I did.

01:21:39.650 --> 01:21:43.850
I walked around and tried to
eavesdrop on your conversations

01:21:43.850 --> 01:21:46.380
so that I could tell what
you were thinking about,

01:21:46.380 --> 01:21:48.230
but without putting
you on the spot,

01:21:48.230 --> 01:21:50.390
without asking you to say,
in front of everybody,

01:21:50.390 --> 01:21:51.410
what you thought.

01:21:51.410 --> 01:21:52.960
So that's one thing to do.

01:21:52.960 --> 01:21:54.937
Now I have a sense for
your mental models,

01:21:54.937 --> 01:21:56.520
how you're thinking
about the problem.

01:21:56.520 --> 01:21:58.610
So I have some really
good information

01:21:58.610 --> 01:22:04.357
about why you think
the answers you think.

01:22:04.357 --> 01:22:06.690
What I'm going to do is I'm
going to give you the chance

01:22:06.690 --> 01:22:08.550
to re-vote.

01:22:08.550 --> 01:22:10.920
If you want to change
your vote, you may.

01:22:10.920 --> 01:22:12.250
Or you don't have to.

01:22:17.500 --> 01:22:19.450
Some of the clicker
software actually

01:22:19.450 --> 01:22:22.600
lets you save
consecutive histograms,

01:22:22.600 --> 01:22:23.450
which can be useful.

01:22:23.450 --> 01:22:26.036
You can compare
if there's change.

01:22:26.036 --> 01:22:27.160
This doesn't let you do it.

01:22:27.160 --> 01:22:28.204
So I just have to--

01:22:28.204 --> 01:22:29.412
AUDIENCE: Voting twice there?

01:22:29.412 --> 01:22:33.974
AUDIENCE: I'm voting
for [INAUDIBLE].

01:22:33.974 --> 01:22:35.370
He's not present, so--

01:22:35.370 --> 01:22:37.460
JANET RANKIN: Voting in
Chicago, early and often.

01:22:50.480 --> 01:22:54.780
We have exactly the
same distribution,

01:22:54.780 --> 01:22:59.264
which flies in the face
of some other data I

01:22:59.264 --> 01:23:00.180
was going to show you.

01:23:00.180 --> 01:23:02.660
But that's OK.

01:23:02.660 --> 01:23:05.010
I'll just in the interest of--

01:23:05.010 --> 01:23:07.170
so one thing I could do
is I could call on you.

01:23:07.170 --> 01:23:09.750
And I could say, OK, if you
said it was lower, tell me

01:23:09.750 --> 01:23:11.030
why you thought it was lower.

01:23:11.030 --> 01:23:13.113
And I could get some
arguments for why you thought

01:23:13.113 --> 01:23:14.460
it was lower on the board.

01:23:14.460 --> 01:23:21.330
So some people think of cellos
make lower sounds than violins.

01:23:21.330 --> 01:23:29.700
And some people think that doors
on mansions have a low sound.

01:23:29.700 --> 01:23:35.730
And other people talked about
xylophones and the length

01:23:35.730 --> 01:23:38.960
and the wavelength
of the xylophone,

01:23:38.960 --> 01:23:44.100
and the longer wavelengths
for the longer pieces.

01:23:44.100 --> 01:23:50.240
So I know a lot about how you're
thinking about this problem.

01:23:50.240 --> 01:23:53.410
The other thing I
know is that I am not

01:23:53.410 --> 01:23:55.150
telling you the answer yet.

01:23:55.150 --> 01:23:57.200
So there's a little bit
of suspense in here.

01:23:57.200 --> 01:24:00.400
There's a little bit to
try to keep you interested

01:24:00.400 --> 01:24:02.944
and wanting to know, wanting
to understand the answer.

01:24:02.944 --> 01:24:03.610
AUDIENCE: Janet?

01:24:03.610 --> 01:24:04.210
JANET RANKIN: Yes?

01:24:04.210 --> 01:24:06.250
AUDIENCE: So you said we
had the same distribution.

01:24:06.250 --> 01:24:08.410
But can we have a show of
hands for how many people

01:24:08.410 --> 01:24:10.310
changed their answer?

01:24:10.310 --> 01:24:12.940
JANET RANKIN: That's
a great question.

01:24:12.940 --> 01:24:13.759
Yes.

01:24:13.759 --> 01:24:15.550
Raise your hand if you
changed your answer.

01:24:18.460 --> 01:24:19.980
It could've been amazing.

01:24:24.490 --> 01:24:27.190
AUDIENCE: So sometimes we've
done that in my physics class.

01:24:27.190 --> 01:24:29.150
When they ask, who
changed their answer?

01:24:29.150 --> 01:24:29.510
And everyone raises their hand.

01:24:29.510 --> 01:24:30.970
It's the same
exact distribution.

01:24:30.970 --> 01:24:33.920
Or everyone goes from
A and B to C and D.

01:24:33.920 --> 01:24:36.504
And even C and D originally
only had three people,

01:24:36.504 --> 01:24:37.670
you'll see the entire shift.

01:24:37.670 --> 01:24:40.032
And it turns out
A and B was right.

01:24:40.032 --> 01:24:42.490
When we vote the second time,
we all picked another answer.

01:24:42.490 --> 01:24:44.620
JANET RANKIN: That's very funny.

01:24:44.620 --> 01:24:45.880
That could have happened.

01:24:45.880 --> 01:24:47.610
Sometimes a nice
follow up question

01:24:47.610 --> 01:24:51.500
is how confident are
you in your answer.

01:24:51.500 --> 01:24:53.780
So then that's a really
good-- because you

01:24:53.780 --> 01:24:55.730
may have 80% of the
people h the right answer

01:24:55.730 --> 01:24:58.220
but if you say how confident
and hardly anybody is

01:24:58.220 --> 01:25:01.650
very confident then, you do
need to talk about it some more.

01:25:01.650 --> 01:25:04.020
So it gives you some really,
really good information.

01:25:04.020 --> 01:25:06.050
So here we go.

01:25:06.050 --> 01:25:06.770
Here's this one.

01:25:12.340 --> 01:25:13.778
It's higher.

01:25:17.430 --> 01:25:18.972
Exact same material.

01:25:18.972 --> 01:25:21.680
AUDIENCE: So when you play
the marimba and the xylophone,

01:25:21.680 --> 01:25:22.950
you have bigger bars.

01:25:22.950 --> 01:25:25.609
That they get really thin
when they're on the bass.

01:25:25.609 --> 01:25:26.900
The bass notes are really thin.

01:25:26.900 --> 01:25:31.654
And the really small high notes,
they're really, really thick.

01:25:31.654 --> 01:25:33.070
JANET RANKIN: So
that's one thing.

01:25:33.070 --> 01:25:34.760
The other thing is
that on a xylophone,

01:25:34.760 --> 01:25:37.950
it's a standing wave, because
you fixed the endpoints.

01:25:37.950 --> 01:25:41.010
And the wave just vibrates
based on the length

01:25:41.010 --> 01:25:44.520
of the pins, the separation
of the pins or the mounts.

01:25:44.520 --> 01:25:48.280
So in this case, it's
a free vibration.

01:25:48.280 --> 01:25:52.176
So that's another
different misconception.

01:25:52.176 --> 01:25:54.675
And then if you think-- so the
easiest way to think about it

01:25:54.675 --> 01:25:55.425
is a diving board.

01:25:55.425 --> 01:25:59.100
If you had a thin diving board,
and you went and jumped on it,

01:25:59.100 --> 01:26:01.350
it would go way down
and come back up again.

01:26:01.350 --> 01:26:03.220
That's a long wavelength.

01:26:03.220 --> 01:26:05.057
And that's a low note.

01:26:05.057 --> 01:26:07.140
And then if you think about
a stiffer diving board

01:26:07.140 --> 01:26:08.970
that you'd be kind of like, mmm.

01:26:08.970 --> 01:26:10.710
That's a shorter wavelength.

01:26:10.710 --> 01:26:11.850
So it's different.

01:26:11.850 --> 01:26:15.120
You have different-- and
then any kind of a cavity,

01:26:15.120 --> 01:26:19.384
like a cello or a door of a
house, if it's a big cavity,

01:26:19.384 --> 01:26:20.550
it's a bigger standing wave.

01:26:20.550 --> 01:26:21.840
It's still a standing wave.

01:26:21.840 --> 01:26:23.670
So those are very different.

01:26:23.670 --> 01:26:25.350
They are different models.

01:26:25.350 --> 01:26:28.320
So this technique
is really great,

01:26:28.320 --> 01:26:32.130
because it really gives you
incredible insight into what

01:26:32.130 --> 01:26:34.200
students' misconceptions are.

01:26:34.200 --> 01:26:36.720
And then you can really
make sure to address

01:26:36.720 --> 01:26:41.350
those misconceptions to deal
with their faulty models.

